eanings":[{"name":"Kavanagh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aidan, Aileen, Brendan, Cathal, Conor, Eamon, Keelin, Liam, Michael Sean, Niall, Ronan, Sean Patrick.","Irish: from <b>Caomhánach</b>, an adjectival epithet meaning ‘belonging to (Saint) <i>Caomhán</i>’, whose personal name means ‘little beautiful one’. Etymologically, the first part of the name is the same as that in   Kevin  .","History: The first known bearer of the epithet was Domhnall Caomhánach (Donal Kavanagh, died in 1175), the son of Diarmait Mac Murchadha (Dermot McMurrough), king of Leinster in the 12th century. Despite being killed at an early age, Domhnall Caomhánach gave his name to a large and important family in Irish history."],"variants":[{"name":"Kinsella","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ciaran, Donal, Finbar, Fintan.","Irish (Wexford and Carlow): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Cinnsealach</b>, or occasionally <b>Ó Cinnsealaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cinnsealach</i>’, an adjectival personal name meaning ‘proud, masterful’ or ‘chief warrior’. <i>Cinnsealach</i> can also indicate a member of the older population grouping called <i>Uí Chinnsealaigh</i>; compare the origin of   Kavanagh  ."]},{"name":"Kevin","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Caoimhín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Caoimhín</i>’ (the personal name <i>Kevin</i>), a name derived from <i>Caémgein</i> ‘comely birth’ although now regarded as a diminutive of Gaelic <i>caomh</i> ‘comely, beloved’. Compare   Kavanagh  ."]},{"name":"Cavanaugh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brennan, Aileen, Dermod, Donal, Patrick Sean.","Irish: variant of   Kavanagh  ."]},{"name":"Cavanah","meanings":["with stress on the first syllable, this is a shortened Anglicized form of <b>Mac Caomhánach</b>, see   Kavanagh  .","alternatively, with stress on <i>-van-</i>, this is a shortened form of <b>McCavana</b>, from <b>Mac an Mhanaigh</b>, ‘son of the monk’ (from <i>manach</i> ‘monk’). This was a Mayo surname, also Anglicized by translation as   Monk   and   Monks  .","Irish:"]},{"name":"Cavender","meanings":["English: most probably a nickname from an Anglo-Norman French equivalent of French <i>chavender</i> ‘chub’ (the fish).","English (of Irish origin): Anglicized form of   Kavanagh   (and its variants, including <b>Cavenagh</b>) or   Cavanna  . Compare   Cavinder  .","History: Hugh Cavenagh (died <i>c.</i> 1709) came from Bristol in England to Westmoreland County, VA, in 1658 as an indentured servant for a five-year period to a Mr. Wills. His descendants spell their name mainly <i>Cavender</i> and <i>Cavinder</i>."]},{"name":"Kaveney","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Géibheannaigh</b> or <b>Mac Géibheannaigh</b>, ‘descendant or son of <i>Géibheannach</i>’, a personal name based on <i>géibheannach</i> meaning ‘bound, or captive one’. There may have been some confusion between this name and   Kavanagh  ."]},{"name":"Cavanagh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brennan, Fergus.","Irish: variant of   Kavanagh  ."]},{"name":"Kavanaugh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Oonagh.","Irish: variant of   Kavanagh  ."]}]},{"name":"Gerald","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>wald</i> ‘rule’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. There has been some confusion with   Gerard .  It died out in England at the end of the 13th century. However, it continued to be popular in Ireland, where it had been brought in the 12th century at the time of Strongbow's invasion. It was used in England in the 17th century and revived in the 19th century, along with several other long-extinct names of Norman, Old English, and Celtic origin, and is now more common than <i>Gerard</i>, which survived all along as an English ‘gentry’ name."],"variants":[{"name":"Jerrold","meanings":["Rare variant of   Gerald  , probably a transferred use of the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gerald Kavanagh was born about 1380, in County Kildare, Ireland. She had at least 1 son with Lord Gerald Kavanagh of Fern."},"et":{"about 1380–":"umbes 1380–Surnud","1370–1431":"1370–1431","1396–1476":"1396–1476","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1476":"1476","1431":"1431","1396":"1396","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","Ferns, County Wexford, Ireland":"Ferns, County Wexford, Iirimaa","County Kildare, Ireland":"County Kildare, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"about 1380–":"noin 1380–Kuollut","1370–1431":"1370–1431","1396–1476":"1396–1476","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","about 1380":"noin 1380","1476":"1476","1431":"1431","1396":"1396","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","Ferns, County Wexford, Ireland":"Ferns, County Wexford, Irlanti","County Kildare, Ireland":"County Kildare, Irlanti"},"fr":{"about 1380–":"environ 1380–Décédée","1370–1431":"1370–1431","1396–1476":"1396–1476","1380–Female":"1380–Décédée","about 1380":"environ 1380","1476":"1476","1431":"1431","1396":"1396","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","Ferns, County Wexford, Ireland":"Ferns, County Wexford, Irlande","County Kildare, Ireland":"County Kildare, Irlande","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gerald Kavanagh est née environ 1380, à County Kildare, Irlande. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Lord Gerald Kavanagh of Fern."},"de":{"about 1380–":"um 1380–Verstorben","1370–1431":"1370–1431","1396–1476":"1396–1476","1380–Female":"1380–Verstorben","about 1380":"um 1380","1476":"1476","1431":"1431","1396":"1396","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","Ferns, County Wexford, Ireland":"Ferns, County Wexford, Irland","County Kildare, Ireland":"County Kildare, Irland","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gerald Kavanagh wurde um 1380 in County Kildare, Ir